@aflyingcowboy31 "The 4090 requires that much power because that's how powerful it is" is both a tautology and outright false, since, y'know, the 4090 has a configurable power target (it literally doesn't even need 450W, it will run just fine albeit a bit slower on 300W). I'm speaking less about the specific 4090 design though and more about the decision to make a 450+W Ada GPU - Nvidia could have made the 4080 as the flagship what with that being lower power yet faster than the previous flagship, but they wanted something that AMD definitely couldn't keep up with. 

(Ignoring dual GPU cards for this discussion): An example of TDP target going down but performance target going up from the AMD side is the R9 Fury X vs Vega 64 - Vega had lower TDP targets yet substantially higher performance. On the Nvidia side there's a few examples I can find, the GTX 285 interestingly was a mid generation refresh that lowered the TDP compared to the GTX 280, the GTX 680 had a significantly lower power target despite significantly higher performance than the preceding 480 (in fact even the 700 series Titans used less power than the 480) and the 10 series cards delivered a massive performance improvement at the same TDP as their predecessors while still not being the highest TDP cards to that time in Nvidia's portfolio. I remembered the timing a bit wrong but I think there's plenty of examples there nonetheless. 

And to be clear, my point wasn't that a drop in TDP gen over gen was common, only that an increase in TDP has never been historically required to keep advancing performance and that there have been drops before. The decision to start cranking up power with Ampere was based on wanting a card that was more expensive than their previous flagship and unambiguously better than anything AMD could deliver, it was not a mandatory part of delivering a generational improvement for anything other than Blackwell really.

@Vortigon I get that - and I also even wrote that things differ between GPU manufacturers so "real frame" was always a bit ambiguous. Or at least there wasn't such a thing as 100% real frame, because it all depended on how information wnet through the software/driver stack and how it was processed by the GPU. So I get that giving it just another layer might be okay.

What I'm worried about is that for example devs might get blamed for something that now it will be out of their control (2 generations in the future - that's games that are in pre-production or early production right now. And there are games that are delayed as well). Or where it will be up to NVIDIA whether they will want to allow your game to be played. Because for example someone might see "sexual themes" in games as "immoral" and NVIDIA in an attempt to look like a "moral company" (I know how it sounds) might make choice to actively un-support it (for now as long as the game uses some API it will be displayed. Though of course it might lack optimizations).

And this applies to all 3 GPU manufacturers, but let's be honest - NVIDIA is basically around 90% of the market. They are already near monopoly in that segment and I seriously don't want them to get even more control.

